Part 1: Data Preparation For HW 6 we chose to go a dataset on students alcohol consumption data.

Student Alcohol Consumption

Stu.Alc <- Student.Alc %>%
  select(sex, age, studytime, Dalc, Walc, health, absences)
Stu.Alc

There are 33 variables in the original dataset, but for our purposes we only need a few. We chose to include the follwoing varibales in a subset dataset of the original dataset: sex, age, studytime, Dalc, Walc, health, absences.

  1. sex - students sex (binary: F - female or M - male)

  2. age - students age (numeric: from 15 to 22)

  3. studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)

  4. Dalc - workday alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  5. Walc - weekend alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  6. health - current health status (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good)

  7. absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93)

Stu.Alc <- Stu.Alc %>%
  mutate(`sex`=ifelse(sex=="F",0,1))
Stu.Alc

Here if sex = 0 then the student is female and if sex = 1 the student is male

Part 2: Single Predictor

logit = function(B0, B1, x) {
    exp(B0+B1*x)/(1+exp(B0+B1*x))
  }
#2
B0 <- summary(LogReg.mod1)$coef[1]
B1 <- summary(LogReg.mod1)$coef[2]

plot(jitter(sex,amount=0.1)~Dalc,data=Stu.Alc)
curve(logit(B0, B1, x),add=TRUE, col="red")

#3
emplogitplot1(sex~studytime, data = Stu.Alc, ngroup="all")

The empirical plot is mostly linear. There is the point at x = 3 that deviates from the line, but the other points are pretty close.

The null hypothesis is that there is no significant relationship between the response variable sex and the predictor variable Dacl if the p-value is not equal to zero.

The alternative hypothesis is that there is a relationship between the response variable sex and the predictor variable Dacl if the p-value is not equal to zero.

Our conclusion since our p-value is very close to zero we can reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is a significant relationship between sex and Dalc.

#5
SE_B1 = summary(LogReg.mod1)$coef[2,2]
exp(B1 - SE_B1*qnorm(0.975))
## [1] 0.3339974
exp(B1 + SE_B1*qnorm(0.975))
## [1] 0.5814965
exp(confint.default(LogReg.mod1))
##                 2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 2.5936260 8.3256067
## studytime   0.3339974 0.5814965

The output gives a 97.5% confidence interval for the odds ratio from 1.5346684 to 2.7246282. We can say with 97.5% confidence that Dalc increases the odds of the student being male, as compared to female, by a factor between 1.5346684 to 2.7246282.

G = summary(LogReg.mod1)$null.deviance - summary(LogReg.mod1)$deviance

G
## [1] 39.22789
1 - pchisq(G, 1)
## [1] 3.771143e-10

The null hypothesis is that the predictor variable Dalc in our model does not have significant relationship with the response variable sex and is not effective at predicting our response variable.

The alternative hypothesis is that the predictor variable Dalc in our model has a significant relationship with the response variable sex and is effective at predicting our response variable.

Our conclusion since our 1 - pchisq(G, 1) is very close to zero we can reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is a significant relationship between sex and the response variable Dalc in our model.
